data.title: When your mechanic gets back to you :(
This concept gives vehicle a spinning cockpit to save people's lives in car collisions

images.description:
Active Cockpit is a crash safety concept designed by Aren Khachatryan that rotates to convert potential energy into kinetic energy in the event of a collision.

The system consists of a horizontal cylindrical space that houses the occupants, seats, and all major controls. Like the airbag sensors in modern cars, it activates only when an impact is detected. Rotation continues even after the vehicle has come to a stop, allowing more distance and time to further dissipate the energy of the impact. It's worth noting that Active Cockpit also works if the vehicle is hit from behind, as the system can rotate both forward and backward.

data.title: Pt. 2! Things I wish I knew before tracking my car

images.description:
I recently posted about my newfound love for auto cross and wanted to encourage other car enthusiasts to get their cars on the track.

The post received a lot of support, and I had a few folks asking for a more technical breakdown of what it took to make it to my first event. 

DISCLAIMER. This is only representative of my limited experience with auto cross (AX) and time attack events. Open lapping is a totally different beast, especially when it comes to heat management and abuse to your car. 

So without further ado, here’s part two of things I wish I knew before tracking my car.

1. Try Before You Buy 

At least at my local track, there are tons of drivers using whatever car they can get their hands on. Stock dailies, clapped out camrys, trucks, vans; if it runs and drives, send it! 

For beginners like myself, driver skill is going to be the limiting factor for how quickly you can get through a course, not the capabilities of the vehicle. 

I’m amazed at how much speed experienced drivers can squeeze out of cars with less than 100 horsepower, because of how much seat time they have at the wheel.

So before you go spending a bunch of money upgrading your ride (or buying a new car altogether), see if this sport is something you want to do long term. Find an event that’s geared toward beginners and get out there.

2. What does an AX run look like?

data.title: Part Two! Things I wish I knew before tracking my car

images.description:
I recently posted about my newfound love for auto cross and wanted to encourage other car enthusiasts to get their cars on the track.

The post received a lot of support, and I had a few folks asking for a more technical breakdown of what it took to make it to my first event. 

DISCLAIMER. This is only representative of my limited experience with auto cross (AX) and time attack events. Open lapping is a totally different beast, especially when it comes to heat management and abuse to your car. 

So without further ado, here’s part two of things I wish I knew before tracking my car.

1. Try Before You Buy 

At least at my local track, there are tons of drivers using whatever car they can get their hands on. Stock dailies, clapped out camrys, trucks, vans; if it runs and drives, send it! 

For beginners like myself, driver skill is going to be the limiting factor for how quickly you can get through a course, not the capabilities of the vehicle. 

I’m amazed at how much speed experienced drivers can squeeze out of cars with less than 100 horsepower, because of how much seat time they have at the wheel.

So before you go spending a bunch of money upgrading your ride (or buying a new car altogether), see if this sport is something you want to do long term. Find an event that’s geared toward beginners and get out there.

2. A working slow car is way more fun than a broken fast car

Even though AX is fairly easy on vehicles, as far as motor sports is concerned, there’s still a lot of abuse that your car will take. The best way to spend your money is to ensure that everything is working properly before crossing the start line.

Not to mention, you’ll have to pass a tech inspection prior to racing. At my local track, this was a self-attest inspection, but it’s important to answer the questions honestly to keep everyone safe.

data.title: Things I wish I knew before tracking my car.

images.description:
TLDR; Track days are the most fun I’ve ever had in a car. The community is amazing, and I have a newfound respect for my car now that I’ve taken it to its limits. My only regret is that I didn’t do it sooner.

Here’s been my experience:

Last year I picked up a 2004 Mazdaspeed Miata, with the intention of modifying it to be a fun weekend street/track car. I picked the MX5 platform because they’re easy to work on, cheap to upgrade, and perform well in the right hands.
After spending a winter upgrading wheels, tires, suspension, adding a roll bar, racing seat, and harness, and performing a lot of maintenance, I was ready for the first event.
